From: vyos-ls1046a-build M3-3 step 1 <noreply@vyos-ls1046a-build>
Date: 2026-05-27
Subject: [PATCH] dpaa: af_xdp_pool - bind NAPI to qmap + arm rx-need-wakeup

M3-3 step 1 (first reviewable slice of Phase 3) per spec sec 5.2 final
paragraph and sec 5.4 RX path step 5.  Two minimal, runtime-observable
behaviour changes inside the af_xdp_pool.ko flavor module:

1. xsk_pool_attach now populates priv->qmap[queue_id].napi with a real
   NAPI context (BSP cpu 0's per-CPU NAPI portal) and sets
   priv->qmap[queue_id].cpu = 0.  Detach already clears the slot via
   the RCU-null + synchronize_net() path that the existing
   xsk_pool_dma_unmap predecessor provides; the napi pointer becomes
   stale only after the percpu_priv goes away on dpaa_remove(), which
   is strictly after every XSK socket on the netdev has been
   unbound -- so READ_ONCE() in xsk_wakeup is safe across the netdev
   lifetime.

   Effect: af_xdp_pool_xsk_wakeup() no longer returns -ENOENT for a
   bound XSK socket.  napi_schedule_irqoff() is now reachable on
   sendto(MSG_DONTWAIT).  Until dedicated per-qband BMan channels +
   per-qband NAPI contexts land in a later M3-3 subpatch, all four
   qbands share cpu 0's NAPI; this is correct because dpaa_fq_to_qband()
   is still the Phase 3a stub that returns 0 for every FQID, so every
   bound qband currently maps to the same RX FQ-set served by cpu 0's
   portal anyway.  Spec sec 5.4 "Queue mapping correctness" items 3-5.

2. af_xdp_pool_xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup() stops being a stub.  For each
   bound xsk_pool[qband] that requested XDP_USE_NEED_WAKEUP at bind
   time (xsk_uses_need_wakeup(pool) == true), assert the rx
   need-wakeup flag via xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup(pool).  Called from
   dpaa_eth_poll() AFTER napi_complete_done() (see core patch 0072).

   Effect: userspace xsk_ring_prod__needs_wakeup() on the fill ring
   now reports 1 when the driver is idle and is waiting for an
   explicit wakeup.  The matching xsk_clear_rx_need_wakeup() lives in
   the RX hot-path branch (later M3-3 subpatch) where it is cleared
   the moment we dequeue any descriptor for a given qband.  Until that
   lands the flag stays asserted across consecutive idle polls -- which
   is correct: there is no ZC RX datapath yet, so the driver IS idle
   and userspace MUST issue an explicit wakeup to resume RX servicing.

This patch is INTENTIONALLY narrow.  It does NOT introduce:
  * the qband RX ZC branch in the per-FD dequeue callback
    (xdp_buff translation + bpf_prog_run_xdp + xdp_do_redirect)
  * NAPI-hooked BMan refill (xsk_buff_alloc_batch + bman_release)
  * the TX ZC path (xsk_tx_peek_release_desc_batch + qman_enqueue)
  * the TxConf -> XSK Completion Ring recycle
  * the xsk_tx_inflight backpressure budget
  * dedicated XSK BMan channels
  * cluster-aware NAPI / CPU pinning

Those land in 0081+ subpatches and gate the >= 7 Gbps M3-3 acceptance.

What is observable on hardware after this patch alone:
  * Existing M2-s2 attach/detach 100x churn loop still passes
    (attach_ok = 102 / detach_ok = 102, no error counter bumps).
  * sudo /tmp/xsk_bind_test eth4 0 --zerocopy --hold 30 returns
    bind() rc = 0 (unchanged from M2-s2).
  * sendto(xsk_fd, ..., MSG_DONTWAIT, ...) now returns 0 instead of
    -ENXIO (-ENOENT mapped) while the socket is bound with
    XDP_USE_NEED_WAKEUP.  Trace this via
    /sys/kernel/tracing/events/napi/napi_poll: a poll event MUST
    fire on cpu 0 within 1 ms of every wakeup.
  * xsk_ring_prod__needs_wakeup(&xsk->fr) returns 1 after each idle
    poll completes when XDP_USE_NEED_WAKEUP was set at bind time.

No throughput change is expected: there is no ZC RX/TX datapath yet.
The patch is a control-plane wiring deliverable.  iperf3 baseline on
DUT must stay within noise of the M2-s2 reference (~945 Mbps on RJ45
eth0 management interface, no FMan ZC traffic).

Build: native arm64 Cobalt 100, FLAVOR=vpp staged tree.  Single .o
target builds clean, no warnings, no new undefined references beyond
the existing M2-s2 set (xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup is a static-inline in
<net/xdp_sock_drv.h>).

Spec reference: specs/dpaa1-afxdp-modernization-spec.md v4.3 sec 5.2
final paragraph + sec 5.4 RX path step 5.
Depends on: 0068, 0069, 0070, 0071, 0072, 0073, 0074, 0075a, 0075b,
            0075c, 0076, 0077, 0079.

Signed-off-by: vyos-ls1046a-build <noreply@vyos-ls1046a-build>
---
diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
index 16afb1d..bfc1506 100644
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/af_xdp_pool/af_xdp_pool_main.c
@@ -263,9 +263,30 @@ return -ENODEV;
 	 * call synchronize_net() before touching any DMA mappings or BMan
 	 * pool state.
 	 */
-	rcu_assign_pointer(priv->xsk_pool[queue_id], pool);
-	priv->xsk_pool_attach_ok++;
-	return 0;
+rcu_assign_pointer(priv->xsk_pool[queue_id], pool);
+
+/*
+ * M3-3 step 1: bind a real NAPI context to this qband so
+ * af_xdp_pool_xsk_wakeup() can schedule it on the userspace
+ * sendto(MSG_DONTWAIT) wakeup path.  Until dedicated per-qband
+ * BMan channels + per-qband NAPI contexts land (later M3-3
+ * subpatch), DPAA1 has one NAPI per online CPU and any of them
+ * will service this qband's RX FQs.  Pick the BSP CPU's NAPI
+ * (cpu 0) — it always exists, and napi_schedule_irqoff() is
+ * cross-CPU safe.  qmap[].cpu/.swp_id/.fqid_base remain 0 for
+ * now; the cluster-aware pin lands with the dedicated channel
+ * subpatch.  Spec sec 5.4 "Queue mapping correctness" item 3-5.
+ */
+{
+struct dpaa_percpu_priv *pcpu;
+
+pcpu = per_cpu_ptr(priv->percpu_priv, 0);
+WRITE_ONCE(priv->qmap[queue_id].napi, &pcpu->np.napi);
+WRITE_ONCE(priv->qmap[queue_id].cpu, 0);
+}
+
+priv->xsk_pool_attach_ok++;
+return 0;
 
 err_unmap:
 	xsk_pool_dma_unmap(pool, DMA_ATTR_SKIP_CPU_SYNC);
@@ -504,10 +525,52 @@ napi_schedule_irqoff(napi);
 return 0;
 }
 
+/*
+ * af_xdp_pool_xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup - arm the XSK rx-need-wakeup flag
+ *
+ * Called from dpaa_eth_poll() AFTER napi_complete_done() and BEFORE
+ * re-arming the QMan DQRR interrupt (see dpaa_eth.c patch 0072).
+ *
+ * For each bound xsk_pool[qband] that requested XDP_USE_NEED_WAKEUP at
+ * bind time (xsk_uses_need_wakeup(pool) == true), assert the rx
+ * need-wakeup flag.  Userspace sees the flag via
+ * xsk_ring_prod__needs_wakeup() on the fill ring and issues
+ * sendto(MSG_DONTWAIT) which lands in af_xdp_pool_xsk_wakeup() and
+ * schedules the NAPI captured in priv->qmap[queue_id].napi.
+ *
+ * The matching xsk_clear_rx_need_wakeup() lives in the RX hot-path
+ * branch (later M3-3 subpatch) where it is cleared the moment we
+ * dequeue any descriptor for a given qband.  Until that lands the
+ * flag stays asserted across consecutive idle polls — which is
+ * correct: userspace knows the driver is idle and that an explicit
+ * wakeup is required to resume RX servicing.
+ *
+ * @np is the per-CPU NAPI portal that just completed its poll; the
+ * spec calls for arming the flag on any pool routed to this portal.
+ * Phase 3a maps every FQID to qband 0 (dpaa_fq_to_qband stub), so
+ * any portal completing a poll arms ALL bound qbands.  Once the
+ * flavor module wires the real qband→portal map (dedicated XSK
+ * BMan channels), this iteration narrows to the portal's qbands.
+ *
+ * Spec sec 5.2 final paragraph + sec 5.4 RX path step 5.
+ */
 static void af_xdp_pool_xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup(struct dpaa_priv *priv,
        struct dpaa_napi_portal *np)
 {
-/* Nothing to do until the ZC datapath lands in patch 0079. */
+struct xsk_buff_pool *pool;
+u16 q;
+
+if (!priv)
+return;
+
+for (q = 0; q < priv->xsk_max_qbands && q < DPAA1_XSK_MAX_QBANDS; q++) {
+pool = rcu_dereference(priv->xsk_pool[q]);
+if (!pool)
+continue;
+if (!xsk_uses_need_wakeup(pool))
+continue;
+xsk_set_rx_need_wakeup(pool);
+}
 }
 
 /* ---------- Ops tables ---------- */
